   =20
      Tim Leissner stuff
   =20
 =20
Tim Leissner, a former Goldman Sachs Group Inc. banker, committed a really =
quite incredible assortment of crimes in connection with the looting of Mal=
aysian sovereign development fund 1MDB. He spent last week  testifying abou=
t those crimes in the New York federal criminal trial of his former underli=
ng, Roger Ng, who is accused of participating in those crimes with him:Amon=
g his many admissions so far: frequently lying to compliance officers, work=
ing on unapproved side deals, trying to get Goldman jobs for the Malaysian =
prime minister=E2=80=99s kids, arranging hundreds of millions of dollars in=
 bribes, pocketing more than $60 million in kickbacks for facilitating 1MDB=
=E2=80=99s bond deals, and getting paid $12 million by Goldman the first ye=
ar he did so.Also bigamy! Somehow he got bigamy into the mix! Double bigamy=
!On Thursday, Leissner also confessed he was twice married to two women at =
the same time. He said he =E2=80=9Cfaked=E2=80=9D a divorce decree in order=
 to marry [Kimora Lee] Simmons while still being married to then-wife, Judy=
 Chan Leissner. He also told jurors he=E2=80=99d earlier falsified a divorc=
e document in order to marry Judy Chan in Hong Kong in about 2000.=E2=80=9C=
I photoshopped the divorce document,=E2=80=9D he said of his 2014 marriage =
to Simmons, a fashion designer.=C2=A0He faked two divorce documents! This i=
s a man who just loves doing fraud.I have to say, I have no particular reas=
on to think that Ng is=C2=A0innocent, but if I were on the jury I would acq=
uit him out of sheer outrage. Even if he did crimes, Leissner was so much=
=C2=A0worse=C2=A0that it is absurd to convict Ng on his testimony. For inst=
ance Leissner didn=E2=80=99t just  steal bribe money from the alleged maste=
rmind of the looting, Malaysian financier Jho Low:When Malaysian financier =
Jho Low, the alleged architect of the massive fraud, asked Leissner to =E2=
=80=9Chold=E2=80=9D 145 million euros ($162 million) in a shell company in =
Mauritius, Leissner saw an opportunity. Because much of his money was inves=
ted in illiquid assets, Leissner told the jury he kept $80 million for hims=
elf.He also stole money from Ng! Or, sorry, =E2=80=9Cborrowed=E2=80=9D it:H=
e said he then borrowed another $1.25 million from Ng, his subordinate at G=
oldman.Leissner said his arrest in 2018 prevented him from repaying Ng any =
of the money. =E2=80=9CI had the intention to pay him back over time but I =
didn=E2=80=99t have a chance,=E2=80=9D he told the jury.Come on. I would le=
t Ng go free and give him his $1.25 million back.Also here are some lazy eu=
phemisms for bribery:Leissner and Ng had code words for their kickbacks tha=
t they would use on BlackBerry Messenger when they worried they might not g=
et the money, Leissner told the court.=E2=80=9CI think it was that the cake=
s or the cookies weren=E2=80=99t coming fast enough,=E2=80=9D he said.Also,=
 one problem with raising $6 billion of bonds for a sovereign-backed develo=
pment fund and then stealing all the money is: How will the fund make inter=
est payments? In a sense that isn=E2=80=99t your problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=
 already stole the money =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in a sense it is, because if th=
e fund defaults on its first payment you are more likely to get caught:Leis=
sner testified to several instances when everything almost fell apart, incl=
uding a moment in which 1MDB neared a default when it missed its first inte=
rest payment on the Magnolia bonds. The lapse tripped alarm bells within Go=
ldman, Leissner said, and risked triggering an investigation that would exp=
ose the whole scam.For Goldman Sachs, a default by 1MDB would be =E2=80=9Ca=
 reputational problem and money problem, because we had, of course, taken $=
200 million out=E2=80=9D of the $1.75 billion. Personally, he said, he fear=
ed an investigation =E2=80=9Cwould uncover, in fact, one of the reasons why=
 there was no money left, which was the scheme.=E2=80=9DI guess the lesson =
is that if you are going to steal all the money you raise in a bond deal, a=
t least leave a few years of coupons in an escrow account to cover your tra=
cks? I don=E2=80=99t know, it doesn=E2=80=99t feel like a very good lesson.
