ately that the market is about to undergo a cataclysmic shift =E2=80=94 and=
 many won't survive the 'washout.'=C2=A0Wall Street Takes Lead in Crypto In=
vestments.=C2=A0New Yorkers Are Locked Out of a  Crypto Coin Made Just for =
Them. WeWork=E2=80=99s Boardroom Lacks a Chairman and Could Soon See  Adam =
Neumann Return. PwC fined over exam cheating involving 1,100 of its auditor=
s. Ukrainian sailor arrested for partially sinking luxury yacht of his Russ=
ian boss in Spain.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy =
email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you=
 can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. T=
hanks![1] An important exception, nearly an objective fact, is gold; some $=
132 billion of Russia=E2=80=99s foreign reserves consists of physical gold.=
 Often that too is an entry on a list =E2=80=94=C2=A0many countries store p=
art of their gold reserves in New York or London, and their gold essentiall=
y consists of a book entry at the New York Fed or the Bank of England =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but in the case of Russia they seem to have physical possession=
 of their gold in Russia. In theory you could subject gold to sanctions =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the U.S. and EU and others could forbid their nationals from bu=
ying gold from the Russian central bank, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in practic=
e that is somewhat less traceable than transactions in electronic dollars. =
On the other hand it is not hugely practical to pay for most goods and serv=
ices in gold bars. The ordinary way to convert gold to goods and services i=
s to *first* convert it into currency, and that=E2=80=99s where the sanctio=
ns hit.[2] Some of the other sanctions also demonstrate that  property righ=
ts are contingent: =E2=80=9CFinancial penalties on Russia agreed by the U.S=
., Canada and key European nations on Saturday include a task force to begi=
n =E2=80=98identifying and freezing assets=E2=80=99 of sanctioned oligarchs=
, government officials and companies. That includes yachts, jets, cars and =
luxury apartments in the West that belong to Russian billionaires, accordin=
g to a U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity to describe the me=
asure.=E2=80=9D
