e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the classroom, one of the ways I suggest =
students think about money is as a kind of social scorecard. You did someth=
ing good =E2=80=94 made something somebody wanted, let somebody else use so=
mething you own, went to work and did everything the boss told you? Good fo=
r you, you get a cookie. Or more precisely, you get a credit, in both sense=
s, in the personal record kept for you at a bank. Now you want something fo=
r yourself? OK, but that is going to be subtracted from the running total o=
f how much you=E2=80=99ve done for the rest for us.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">People get very excited about China=E2=80=99s social credit system=
, a sort of generalization of the =E2=80=9Cpermanent record=E2=80=9D we use=
 to intimidate schoolchildren. And=C2=A0ok, it does sound kind of dystopian=
. If your rating is too low, you aren=E2=80=99t allowed to fly on a plane. =
Think about that =E2=80=94 a number assigned to every person, adjusted base=
d on somebody=E2=80=99s judgment of your pro-social or anti-social behavior=
. If your number is too low, you can=E2=80=99t on a plane. If it=E2=80=99s =
really low, you can=E2=80=99t even get on a bus. Could you imagine a system=
 like that in the US?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except, of course, th=
at we have exactly this system already. The number is called a bank account=
. The difference is simply that we have so naturalized the system that =E2=
=80=9Chow much money you have=E2=80=9D seems like simply a fact about you, =
rather than a judgment imposed by society.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
