om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason to go public by merging wit=
h a=C2=A0special purpose acquisition company is that you get to include pro=
jections of future earnings in your prospectus marketing the deal to invest=
ors, whereas in a traditional U.S. initial public offering you are limited =
to reporting historical financials. If you are a company with no real histo=
ry of selling products, it is far more pleasant to raise money on projected=
 future revenue than on historical lack of revenue. The incentives and bias=
es here are pretty obvious: You go public because you expect to have high f=
uture revenue, you want to project high future revenue because that will ge=
t you more investors at a higher stock price, and, crucially, your future r=
evenue is entirely unpredictable because you don=E2=80=99t have any real re=
venue now. So you would naturally expect most pre-revenue companies that go=
 public by SPAC to miss their projections.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">So this is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
6861424.278604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zcGFjLXN0YXJ0dXBzLW1h=
ZGUtbG9mdHktcHJvbWlzZXMtdGhleS1hcmVudC13b3JraW5nLW91dC0xMTY0NTc4NTAzMQ/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB05bf9171" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sort of amazing</a>?</p><blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dozens of startups that went public in a pande=
mic-fueled stock market frenzy are missing the projections they used to win=
 over investors, many by substantial margins and just a few months after ma=
king those forecasts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nearly half of all st=
artups with less than $10 million of annual revenue that went public last y=
ear through a special-purpose acquisition company, known as SPAC, have fail=
ed or are expected to fail to meet the 2021 revenue or earnings targets the=
y provided to investors, according to a Wall Street Journal analysis.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The underperformance of these nascent companies =
=E2=80=94 most of them tech startups =E2=80=94 bolsters one of the biggest =
concerns many investors and others raised about the SPAC boom of the past t=
wo years. Critics of SPACs say the loosely regulated going-public process a=
llows startups to attract investors with bullish financial projections, des=
pite having little or no revenue in their history. ...</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">The Journal=E2=80=99s analysis covered the 63 companies that we=
nt public through a SPAC deal last year and had less than $10 million in tr=
ailing sales at the time of their listing. Of those 63, at least 30 didn=E2=
=80=99t meet their projections, according to the Journal=E2=80=99s analysis=
 of data provided by Jay Ritter, a University of Florida professor who stud=
ies public listings, and from FactSet. A total of 199 SPAC deals were compl=
eted last year.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The revenue cutoff was desi=
gned to capture companies with no or very little commercial production. The=
 Journal compared the companies=E2=80=99 initial projections with either an=
alysts=E2=80=99 estimates from FactSet, updated company forecasts or earnin=
gs reports.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ignore the phrasin=
g there: That is reporting that=C2=A0<em>more than half of pre-revenue-ish =
SPACs met their (early) revenue projections</em>. I would have taken the un=
der!=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
